> The SkiaRenderingEngine provides dirty region optimization for efficient partial redraws, ensuring that only changed portions of the UI are re-rendered each frame.

> With 35+ Skia-based view implementations, OpenMaui achieves 100% MAUI API compliance, allowing existing MAUI applications to run on Linux with minimal or no code changes.

> The dual-mode rendering strategy—GPU acceleration with automatic software fallback—ensures OpenMaui works reliably across diverse Linux hardware configurations.

sections.content:
At the heart of OpenMaui's rendering system is the **SkiaRenderingEngine**, a sophisticated pipeline that manages the complete lifecycle of frame rendering—from dirty region tracking to final pixel output.

## Core Rendering Pipeline

The rendering engine orchestrates several critical subsystems:

```csharp
public class SkiaRenderingEngine
{
    // Dirty region optimization
    private readonly DirtyRegionTracker _dirtyRegions;

    // Frame scheduling
    private readonly FrameScheduler _scheduler;

    // GPU/software rendering abstraction
    private readonly IRenderBackend _backend;

    public void Render(SKCanvas canvas, SKRect clipRect)
    {
        // 1. Collect dirty regions
        var dirtyRects = _dirtyRegions.GetDirtyRegions();

        // 2. Clip to minimize drawing
        canvas.ClipRect(clipRect);

        // 3. Traverse view hierarchy
        RenderViewTree(canvas, dirtyRects);

        // 4. Flush to GPU/screen
        canvas.Flush();
    }
}
```

## View Hierarchy Traversal

OpenMaui implements **35+ Skia-based view classes** that form a complete UI toolkit:

**Layout Containers:**
- `SkiaStackLayout` - Vertical/horizontal stacking with spacing
- `SkiaGrid` - Row/column grid with Auto, Star, and Absolute sizing
- `SkiaAbsoluteLayout` - Absolute positioning with proportional flags
- `SkiaFlexLayout` - Flexbox-style layout with wrap and alignment
- `SkiaScrollView` - Scrollable container with virtualization

**Input Controls:**
- `SkiaButton`, `SkiaImageButton` - Command-bound buttons with visual states
- `SkiaEntry`, `SkiaEditor` - Text input with IME support (IBus, Fcitx5, XIM)
- `SkiaCheckBox`, `SkiaSwitch`, `SkiaRadioButton` - Selection controls
- `SkiaSlider`, `SkiaStepper` - Numeric input
- `SkiaDatePicker`, `SkiaTimePicker`, `SkiaPicker` - Specialized pickers

**Display Controls:**
- `SkiaLabel` - Text with font fallback for emoji/CJK via HarfBuzz
- `SkiaImage` - Image display with SVG support, GIF animation, and caching
- `SkiaProgressBar`, `SkiaActivityIndicator` - Progress feedback

**Advanced Controls:**
- `SkiaCollectionView` - Virtualized lists with selection and headers
- `SkiaCarouselView` - Horizontal scrolling with indicators
- `SkiaWebView` - WebKitGTK integration
- `SkiaGraphicsView` - Custom drawing surface with `IDrawable`

Each view implements the core `IView` interface:

```csharp
public interface IView
{
    void Draw(SKCanvas canvas, SKRect dirtyRect);
    void Measure(double widthConstraint, double heightConstraint);
    void Arrange(SKRect bounds);
    void Invalidate(); // Triggers repaint
}
```

## Handler Architecture

OpenMaui provides **40+ handler implementations** that map MAUI controls to Skia views:

```csharp
public class ButtonHandler : ViewHandler<IButton, SkiaButton>
{
    public static IPropertyMapper<IButton, ButtonHandler> Mapper =
        new PropertyMapper<IButton, ButtonHandler>(ViewHandler.ViewMapper)
        {
            [nameof(IButton.Text)] = MapText,
            [nameof(IButton.TextColor)] = MapTextColor,
            [nameof(IButton.Command)] = MapCommand,
            [nameof(IButton.Background)] = MapBackground,
            // 100% MAUI API coverage
        };

    protected override SkiaButton CreatePlatformView()
    {
        return new SkiaButton();
    }

    private static void MapText(ButtonHandler handler, IButton button)
    {
        handler.PlatformView.Text = button.Text;
        handler.PlatformView.Invalidate();
    }
}
```

This architecture ensures that all MAUI properties—`Color`, `Rect`, `Size`, `Thickness`, `double`—map seamlessly to Skia rendering primitives, maintaining **100% API compatibility** with existing MAUI applications.

## Integration with Native Windowing

The rendering engine integrates with both GTK and X11 windowing systems:

**GTK Integration:**
```csharp
public class GtkSkiaSurfaceWidget
{
    // Embeds Skia canvas in GTK widget
    private SKSurface _surface;

    protected override bool OnDrawn(Cairo.Context cr)
    {
        using var canvas = _surface.Canvas;
        _renderingEngine.Render(canvas, GetClipRect());
        return true;
    }
}
```

**X11 Direct Rendering:**
```csharp
public class X11Window
{
    private SKSurface _surface;

    private void OnExposeEvent()
    {
        using var canvas = _surface.Canvas;
        _renderingEngine.Render(canvas, _damageRect);
        XFlush(_display);
    }
}
```

This dual-backend approach supports both traditional X11 environments and modern GTK-based desktops, with **Wayland support** via `WaylandWindow` for next-generation Linux systems.

Performance is critical for desktop applications. OpenMaui implements a sophisticated **dual-mode rendering strategy** that leverages GPU acceleration when available while gracefully falling back to software rendering on constrained hardware.

## GPU Rendering with OpenGL

The `GpuRenderingEngine` uses **OpenGL-backed Skia surfaces** for hardware acceleration:

```csharp
public class GpuRenderingEngine : IRenderBackend
{
    private GRContext _grContext;
    private SKSurface _gpuSurface;

    public void Initialize()
    {
        // Create OpenGL context
        var glInterface = GRGlInterface.Create();
        _grContext = GRContext.CreateGl(glInterface);

        // Create GPU-backed surface
        var frameBufferInfo = new GRGlFramebufferInfo(
            fboId: 0,
            format: GRPixelConfig.Rgba8888.ToGlSizedFormat()
        );

        var renderTarget = new GRBackendRenderTarget(
            width: _windowWidth,
            height: _windowHeight,
            sampleCount: 0,
            stencilBits: 8,
            glInfo: frameBufferInfo
        );

        _gpuSurface = SKSurface.Create(
            _grContext,
            renderTarget,
            GRSurfaceOrigin.BottomLeft,
            SKColorType.Rgba8888
        );
    }

    public void Render(Action<SKCanvas> drawCallback)
    {
        var canvas = _gpuSurface.Canvas;
        drawCallback(canvas);

        // Flush GPU commands
        canvas.Flush();
        _grContext.Flush();
    }
}
```

## Automatic Software Fallback

When GPU rendering fails (missing drivers, headless environments, or resource constraints), OpenMaui seamlessly switches to **CPU-based rendering**:

```csharp
public class SoftwareRenderingEngine : IRenderBackend
{
    private SKSurface _cpuSurface;
    private SKBitmap _backBuffer;

    public void Initialize()
    {
        _backBuffer = new SKBitmap(
            _windowWidth,
            _windowHeight,
            SKColorType.Rgba8888,
            SKAlphaType.Premul
        );

        _cpuSurface = SKSurface.Create(_backBuffer.Info, _backBuffer.GetPixels());
    }

    public void Render(Action<SKCanvas> drawCallback)
    {
        var canvas = _cpuSurface.Canvas;
        drawCallback(canvas);

        // Copy to window framebuffer
        CopyToFramebuffer(_backBuffer);
    }
}
```

## Backend Selection Strategy

OpenMaui detects the optimal rendering backend at startup:

```csharp
public class RenderBackendSelector
{
    public IRenderBackend SelectBackend()
    {
        // 1. Try GPU rendering first
        if (IsOpenGLAvailable())
        {
            try
            {
                var gpuBackend = new GpuRenderingEngine();
                gpuBackend.Initialize();
                return gpuBackend;
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                // Log and fall through
            }
        }

        // 2. Fall back to software rendering
        var softwareBackend = new SoftwareRenderingEngine();
        softwareBackend.Initialize();
        return softwareBackend;
    }

    private bool IsOpenGLAvailable()
    {
        // Check for OpenGL 2.0+ support
        return CheckGLVersion() >= new Version(2, 0);
    }
}
```

## Performance Characteristics

**GPU Rendering Benefits:**
- **60 FPS animations**: Smooth scrolling and transitions
- **Complex effects**: Shadows, gradients, and blurs with minimal CPU overhead
- **Large surfaces**: Efficient rendering of high-resolution displays (4K+)
- **Reduced power consumption**: GPU hardware is optimized for graphics workloads

**Software Rendering Use Cases:**
- **Headless environments**: CI/CD pipelines, automated testing
- **Legacy hardware**: Systems without OpenGL support
- **Virtual machines**: Where GPU passthrough isn't available
- **Remote desktop**: X11 forwarding or VNC scenarios

